##I answered the AIDS helpline in Hubei Province

Wechat media-fox

Features, for those who insist on serious reading options. Sohu News Extreme Day studio.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Xiao Chao (first from the right) before doing aids and anti-drug publicity in the community. Photo courtesy of the respondents

ABSTRACT: Xiao Chao is an AIDS drug shortage hotline operator in the Yichang Branch of the Wuhan Center. From the start of the epidemic to the beginning of March, his center in Wuhan has sent more than 7,200 boxes of drugs to more than 800 AIDS patients. Founded in 2011, the Wuhan Center for Gays and Lesbians is a nonprofit organization that promotes LGBT community services and public education.

Working as an AIDS activist in Yichang for more than four years, she was in her first contact with so many infected people -- from students in her twenty to people in their 70s and 80s, some with just three or four days'worth of drugs left, some have been off their meds for a month or two. The outbreak has squeezed their privacy, and many are torn between exposing their medical history, seeking help and risking withdrawal.

Editor Tao Ruogu

"Why go out? " Asked after the road closure, they might reply "to get rabies shots. " Some even cut themselves with a knife to make it look real. Also may answer, got chronic nephritis, diabetes, hypertension, want to go out to fetch medicine. Excuses abound, but the truth never comes out, as if you were on AIDS.

As of the end of October 2018, there were about 20,000 HIV / AIDS patients in Hubei Province and about 6,000 in Wuhan, Hubei Daily and Changjiang daily reported. From late February until now, Xiao's phone has been ringing off the hook. He sits in his living room all day, receiving an average of more than 100 calls a day for help. He registers information about AIDS patients'drug shortages.

He handled the situation on the other end of the phone carefully. Patients are anxious tone, some people do not usually in the local medicine, acquaintances of society, relatives and friends in the medical disease control system work, easy to cause gossip, but go next to the county road cut off. There is also the attitude of the elderly patients, too embarrassed to tell their families, will not use smartphones, information occlusion, think has a foot into the loess, thought to give up.

After registering the patients, Xiao's colleagues then went to the hospital to register them, verify files, and take medicine, addressing the needs of 60 to 80 people a day. When they mail it, they wrap it in layers, don't tell the courier what it's for, and then destroy the information on time.

Xiao Chao's partner packed up the medicine from the hospital in his office. It was packed and shot in the early hours of the day, sometimes overnight to get it out early. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Drug withdrawal

I have never been in contact with so many AIDS patients, this period of time alone in the mobile phone added more than 1,000 wechat friends, calls every day to call hundreds of times.

It's easier to pay attention when you're on the phone. When I answer the phone, I ask, "what can I do for you? " The first thing I do to check information is, "is this a good time to talk? "

A lot of patients don't tell their families, they stay together during the outbreak, they whisper on the phone, and if they mumble, I'll read them one by one in a different way, and they'll just say "yes" or "No. " If not, we'll do it another time. Someone gets a call, they hang up, I change the text.

After the outbreak began, we (Wuhan Center) opened a help line for AIDS patients, from January 26 to February 15, mainly to provide counseling services, tell them the CDC at all levels of the latest policy, special times how to get drugs in different places.

They range from students in their twenty to people in their 70s and 80s. Some live in remote villages and try every means to get a pass to get out of the village, but the road is cut off, or piled with large stones and can not walk, at least sixty kilometers away from the nearest designated hospital to get medicine, and even thought about walking, give Up.

AIDS patients need to take medicine every day, once stopped, there will be the risk of drug resistance, according to individual differences, varying degrees. Patients need to go to a hospital for a viral load test to know that if the viral load continues to zero, there is no resistance, but if it rises too high, the drug is no longer useful to the patient and requires replacement with second-line drugs or expensive out-of-pocket drugs.

On the other hand, the drug is to inhibit the virus in the human body reproduction, withdrawal of drugs, HIV will reproduce, replication, attack the body's immune system. When the patient's immunity drops, a small cold may be repeated, not easy to good, the risk of Opportunistic infection will increase, many elderly people have basic diseases, immunity once dropped, more worrying.

In mid-february, the situation of "closing cities" in Hubei Province became more and more serious. Many AIDS patients could not leave the community. When we thought of mailing drugs and helping more people, we contacted the love clinic of Jinyintan Hospital, together with our Yichang branch (Yichang counterpart social work centre) and Wuhan Weixian Social Work Centre, we have launched the drug mailing service.

We have also set up a volunteer convoy to collect drugs, sending about 60-80 doses a day, each of which can be administered for more than a month.

Colleagues who went to collect medicine got up at 7 am, put on protective clothing, masks and goggles, and drove to the Golden Pool Hospital, the only Infectious Disease Hospital in Wuhan, where most of the local AIDS patients are treated, it is now the most heavily infected hospital in the United States, Florida, where more than 60 people with AIDS are registered, filed and treated for a full day.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Volunteers collect, verify and count drugs in the Golden Pool. Photo courtesy of the respondents

The drug mailing registration form (the system) was launched on February 17. I and another colleague is responsible for the hotline, and direct contact with AIDS patients, and two colleagues are responsible for the summary of information and mailing address.

From 9:00 a.m. to 12:00 p.m. , we kept answering the phone, and the next day, we called to check that the information was correct. Every day cell phone ring to the maximum, the phone from morning to night did not stop, listening to a headache, I almost every day to change the ring.

In addition to registration, it is necessary to verify and compare patient information and hospital files. Patients can not send what they say they want. AIDS follows the principle of territorial management, if not in the gold and Silver Pool Hospital treatment, patients need the original hospital to open a letter, then go to the gold and Silver Pool Hospital medicine.

There are patients in other hospitals for fear of not receiving medicine, will deliberately say their treatment in the gold and Silver Pool Hospital, but volunteers to the hospital, check the file, can not get medicine, in fact, a waste of time.

Some people are very anxious and ask several times a day: "Have you registered my information? When did you send it? How many days can it arrive? " I can understand their worry, will be patiently informed that the general is three days to send, Wuhan City around a day to Hubei five to eight days to other places, they want to reserve enough time for themselves.

Some time ago, a girl came to me for help. When she filled out the information form, she said she had forgotten the name of the medicine and wanted to look at the bottle. She filled it out again and missed the time of the day. She was very worried.

The day we got pulled over for the drugs, our volunteer pass was broken, and this girl was helping us look for a car. She called me almost nonstop all day, several times, and I was a little puzzled, everyone is waiting in line for the medicine, why is she so anxious?

Finally, she told me that she was to give her father, her father only three or four days of medicine, every day in bed, did not get out of bed for half a month, trance, call him also ignore people, she worried that his father will not open.

She wasn't listed that day, so she didn't get her meds from the hospital the next day, and when we found out about her, we found out about her emergency meds, and we sent them to her.

There are also many elderly people who come to us for help alone. The rate of AIDS among the elderly has increased in recent years.

Talking on the phone with many elderly infected people, the most sad thing is to hear that I have one foot in the loess, this disease is embarrassing, I am ashamed to tell others, my family does not accept it, so I will do what I have to do, thank you for caring about me.

I have never been exposed to elderly AIDS patients, they are in particular need of understanding and warmth.

A lot of people don't know how to use their smartphones, and they don't know how to get help, so they have to go to the hospital, and the hospital gives them our contact information, and they call us. Some old people can only speak dialect, it is very difficult to express. It usually takes only 10 minutes to register information, and it may take me half an hour to ask again and again, to confirm every word, some old people hear me not to hear a word, anxious like a child, constantly raising the volume, repeat.

An old man called, said he lived alone, can help deliver medicine, tone carefully. Then there are the old men who say they've been off their meds for more than 10 days, a month, and I wonder why I didn't ask for help sooner, as if I regretted saying it -- where did they go for help?

They don't seem to do much in our opinion, but they will be especially touched and thanked by Wechat or by phone.

When a woman in her 60s found us, she was crying on the phone. She said she couldn't get down the stairs because of her leg. She had only one or two days of medicine left. "Help me. ". And then when she gets the pills, she's GonNa be all, "I saved your life. ".

And then when I sent it out, she liked it a lot. Recently, I saw that she was in good condition. She bought vegetables in a group in Wuhan. She also sent pictures of friend circle, a small cart, to buy vegetables in a group.

Also met a middle-aged male AIDS patients, I according to the regular process and his communication, fill out the form, there is no more communication, only know that he is the company. But one time my friend posted a lack of supplies status, he suddenly contact me, said his company has a few bottles of alcohol, can send us.

Then we met with an emergency and were delayed in getting medicine the next day. Although the elder brother's medicine had been collected the day before, he was not affected, but he was still very excited and worried about what would happen to the medicine of other infected people. He helped us to call various hotlines, and he wants to make a donation.

After he received the medicine, he sent me a full screen of wechat voice, said to get express, all the way while walking and crying. His family knew he was sick, and they cried when we sent them.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Volunteers take medicine to lunch

Someone needs to pay attention to minorities

AIDS is already a controlled, preventable chronic disease, and with medication, people live like normal people, but we did a survey, and if we had to choose between leukemia and AIDS, more people [ it is the lesser of two evils to...; would rather... ] would choose leukemia. One of the three routes of transmission of AIDS is sexual transmission, anti-discrimination for so many years, there is still stigma.

Previously, patients said they were afraid not only that people would discriminate against them if they knew, but also that they would give special attention. For example, when they live in the same dormitory, they don't kick out the AIDS patients, but they all move out one by one, leaving the AIDS patients alone. They say, "look, we didn't discriminate against you. We moved out ourselves. " But what AIDS patients really need is ordinary treatment.

So a lot of patients will not be in the local medicine, small place, even have relatives and friends in the medical disease control system work, it is easy to cause gossip, they will go next to the county and city medicine.

This epidemic has further reduced the privacy of AIDS patients.

Someone went out to get medicine for a car and made all kinds of phone calls, even 110, but the police were also very busy. Finally, they came across a car to go out. Unexpectedly, his relative happened to be in the car. He was a doctor on an emergency call. He got into this car, but you have to hide it from your relatives.

We help people with AIDS send medicines, from wiring to receiving medicines to sending parcels, every link of the staff and volunteers signed a privacy and confidentiality agreement, everyone has access to information has a classification, once the leak will bear legal responsibility, in addition, form Information, courier information, will be destroyed immediately every day.

Packed Express Mail, when the volunteers to the outside of the drug wrapped several layers, also did not tell the courier medicine to treat what disease, and then destroy the help-seekers information on time. Photo courtesy of the respondents

It also occurred to us that many people might be traumatized by the fact that they would have to be questioned unwillingly, or even given away their privacy, to get their medicine, and then how would they move on? That's why I've set up a psych line.

But the helpline isn't as effective as the pill line. If there are some mental disorders, they may seek professional help, but at present many are just serious anxiety, they feel talk, not solve the problem, rather than direct mail to practical.

As one of our counselors said, asking someone if they want to see a counselor can lead to a defensive "I'm not sick" mentality, so we are also rethinking and adjusting our counseling hotline.

After graduating in 2018, I went to work in the Yichang branch of the Wuhan Center for gays and Lesbians, working full time on HIV testing and prevention advocacy. In small places to promote this kind of work is very difficult, some AIDS patients prefer to join the national wechat group, also do not want to show their face in any local group. Some patients go to get medicine, hats, masks, sunglasses are heavily armed, very afraid of being recognized. Some people a listen to me is to do AIDS work, the subconscious body back a step.

In the beginning, I was the only one in Yichang, but now I have a team of five, working not only with people living with AIDS, but also with sex education, anti-drug education for young people, protection of girls against sexual assault, and some interaction with government departments.

I've been discriminated against and deported for this job before. In the spring of 2019, we set up stalls in the residential area to publicize our knowledge of AIDS prevention and testing. The staff in the residential area and on the street recognized us. However, when one of the owners saw it, it happened in the group of owners. All of a sudden dozens of owners came and surrounded us, and the police, and the old ladies in their 70s and 80s, to talk sense into us and tell us to move. They think that AIDS is dirty, but also affect housing prices in the community.

My family also do not understand, learn from an early age, obedient child, why medical school graduates to find such a job? Now my parents are trying to accept me, but there are relatives back home who always ask, "what job is Chao Chao Chao now looking for? " My mother will still be embarrassed to say, just say, "it seems to be doing some volunteers, do not understand. ".

Someone needs to focus on minorities and give them confidence.

I remember once, on a business trip, I met a friend on a train, and he talked about aids-related knowledge, I talk a little loud, and more and more energetic, and later around a number of strangers are listening to me very carefully, know something, and then you'll feel the job.

This outbreak has made everyone's lives more precious. AIDS patients who are about to go off their medication have experienced a crisis. Everyone has gone through a complicated mental journey. After that, they will pay more attention to the details of their lives, including going out and getting more medicines.
